"History: Daniel Sargent <i>dit</i> Sérien and Langlais from Worcester, MA married Marguerite Lavoie in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1718. Joseph Weber <i>dit</i> Langlais from Boston, MA married Marie-Charlotte Guillet in Cap Saint-Ignace, QC, in 1725."]},{"name":"Longley","meanings":["English (mainly Nottinghamshire and South Yorkshire): variant of   Langley  . Compare   Longpre   2."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":16,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma Langley was born about 1243, in Shropshire, England, her father, Sir Geoffrey Langley, was 44 and her mother, Alinore Montfort, was 27. She married John Peyvre before 1262. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1272, at the age of 30."},"et":{"Abt 1243–1272":"umbes 1243–1272","1231–Male":"1231–Surnud","1243–1272":"1243–1272","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1253–Male":"1253–Surnud","–1275":"–1275","1237–1267":"1237–1267","1262–1315":"1262–1315","1200–1274":"1200–1274","1217–